ongoing uses locks (not defined in this file, but used a lot), let mut ongoing = self.ongoing.lock(), add, cancel, preload_paged, limit all use ongoing, this is shared because all tasks neet to be trackable by id, and cancellation needs to be visible across threads, locks are short lived, let task = ongoing.add(r#in);self.behavior.update(task.id);self.file.submit(r#in, LOW); -> lock regisry, create task, release lock, dispach to worker queue -> shared memory used for coordination, if let Some(hook) = self.ongoing.lock().cancel(id) {
    self.hook.submit(hook, HIGH);
}-> canceling checks the shared state and schedules a follow up task. No shared memory between workers. let throttle = Arc::new(Throttle::new(...)) -> multiple tasks use the same rate limiter = shared coordination primitive. self.preload.loading.lock().put(hash, id) -> only one preload per file -> deduplication + coordination. pub fn fetch_paged(&self, fetcher: Arc<Fetcher>, targets: Vec<File>) -> reused fetcher, pub fn preload_paged(&self, preloader: Arc<Preloader>, target: &File) -> shared preloader coordinating background loading

impl Ran {
  pub(crate) fn mutex(&self, recipe: &Recipe, arguments: &[Vec<String>]) -> Arc<Mutex<bool>> {
    self
      .0
      .lock()
      .unwrap()
      .entry(recipe.recipe_path().clone())
      .or_default()
      .entry(arguments.into())
      .or_default()
      .clone()
  }
}
